# Prime Order

A direct consequence of the Theorem of Lagrange states that a group of prime order must be cyclic.

<div class="proof">

Let $G$ be of prime order $p$, and let $a$ be an element of $G$ different from the identity. Then the cyclic
subgroup $\lrangle{a}$ of $G$ generated by $a$ has at least two elements, $a$ and $e$. But since all subgroups
must have an order that divides $G$ by the Theorem of Lagrange, $\lrangle{a}$ must have order $m \geq 2$ that
divides $p$. Therefore $\left|\lrangle{a}\right} = p$ so $G$ is cyclic.

</div>

